NarNarrative: The porcupine fish protects itself by swelling up and erecting the spines all over its body: it does this by swallowing water. Unfortunately, this has made them attractive to collectors and novelty dealers, who collect the fish and sell their dried bodies., The porcupine fish protects itself by swelling up and erecting the spines all over its body: it does this by swallowing water. Unfortunately, this has made them attractive to collectors and novelty dealers, who collect the fish and sell their dried bodies.

This strange example of Victorian taxidermy consists of two Pike. One is trying to eat the other and the second fish has become stuck in its throat so both fish have died. We don't know whether the fish actually died in this way.

Unlike most other bony fishes, Sturgeons have large, thin, boney plates instead of scales. This skull was mounted, nose upwards, on a brass support by Thomas Atthey in the 19th century. Minute holes were bored in the bones and thin wire threaded through and twisted to hold them exactly in place. This specimen used tp be covered by a glass dome.

This skeleton is of a female Thornback Ray or Roker, and her size suggests that she is immature. Thornback rays can grow to be 85 cm (34 in.) long and 61 cm (24 in.) wide. The largest ones are usually females. The name Thornback is due to their large thornlike scales, known as bucklers, on the back and sides of the males and on the underside as well in females. Roker is the local name. They are the most common rays found in shallow British waters, in muddy or sandy areas.

This is the snout of a Sawfish, which is a type of ray. The Sawfish slashes its 'saw' back and forth as it swims through a school of fish, usually in shallow water, which disables enough of them to be easy prey. The Sawfish also uses its 'saw' to stir up the ocean bottom in a similar way. Sawfish are found in tropical waters and they can grow to be 6metres (20ft.) long. The longest 'saws', 2metres (6ft.) or more, were often brought back to Britain as souvenirs.

This trout skull was prepared during the 1800s by Thomas Atthey of Newcastle. The bones are wired together almost exactly as they are in the living fish. Trout generally live in freshwater but are also known to feed in the sea. They eat insects and small invertebrates (animals without backbones) that live or hatch in water. Trout are found in many lakes and streams in Britain.

The Chub is a freshwater fish of the carp family, members of which have teeth in the throat instead of the jaws. They grind against a hard horny pad in the roof of the throat and are known as pharyngeal teeth. Each type of fish in this family has distinctive teeth. The bony gill cover, or operculum, shows growth rings rather in the same way as tree rings do. In this specimen they indicate that the fish was 8 to 9 years old when it died. It came from the River Eden and had lived in the Hancock Museum for 3 years.

ColPhysicalDescription: Cranium, otoliths, dorsal spine, vertebrae and tail fin.
NarNarrative: Not a lot is known about this family of sea catfish. They are found in tropical coastal waters and lakes of the eastern USA and the Philipines. The eggs are incubated in the mouth of the male, and sometimes the female. Some species, such as this one, have a stout, hinged spine on top of the skull. All the Crucifix Catfish have bony structures looking like the figure of a man with outstretched arms on the underside of the skull.

Varieties of Angler Fishes occur world wide. They are all marine fish and bottom-living, usually in deep water. They have a fishing lure, like a bait, on their heads which can entice prey into their vicinity. Their extra wide mouths, have long, strong, teeth and are very quick to grab any fishes which come too close. Otherwise they move very slowly when swimming, and their fins are not very powerful. They are fairly common around the British Isles

The otolith is an earbone which is used for balance in some bony fishes. In the cod family it is different for each variety. This is the otolith of a Hake and is different from the other cod family members except other Hakes. It is also possible to tell the age of the fish from the number of ridges in the otolith. These ridges can be seen best if the picture is enlarged. At the lower left edge of the bone, where they are most recent, they are very clear.

This is the front end of a garfish which has been dried whole, and the natural colour has been lost. The bones of the Garfish family are often greeen, and the larger varieties make good eating. This is the local variety which is a surface living, fast swimming predator of temperate seas and grows to about 37in (94.0 cm).

Sticklebacks are small fishes and this one, at about 15.0 cm (6ins) is the largest one occurring in Northern Europe. It is a marine species and was found in a dried state with nearly all the bones visible, but it has lost most of its fins.

The dark appearance of this specimen may be because of the long time it has been on display. The skull is an unusual shape, with two bony projections extending forward. Some of the spines which cover the bony armour can be seen along the line of the dorsal fin. Members of this family are carnivorous bottom livers, and can make grunting noises produced by their large air bladder.

This is a Barracuda jaw, and most of its teeth are present. It is very dark coloured because, as the label says, it has been in the Hancock Collection for many years. The sizes of the 18 varieties of Barracuda range from 50cm (20ins) to 2M (6ft). They are all carnivorous and fast swimmers, and the larger ones can be more of a danger to divers than sharks.

When adult, Scads are 25 to 50cm (10 to 20ins) long. There is a row of heavy bony scutes (scales) along each side of the body, some of which can be seen near the tail of this specimen. Young Scads are found inshore, the older ones living in shoals out at sea. The young fish feed on plankton, while the adults take fishes and small squid.

The bill fishes are all large and mainly caught for sport and food, rather than museums, so not a lot is known about them. They are all large, fast predatory swimmers, but could one of them swim fast enough to drive its bill through 6.0 cm (two and a half inches) of solid wood? This plank has been split in half, apparently by the fish, but there is another hole beside it which has been filled in

Deal Fish are thin bodied and grow up to 2.5m long (about 8ft). They feed on deep water fish, squids and shrimps. Their mouths are protrusible, thrusting the jaws forwards when feeding. The photo shows the jaws outstretched in this way.
LocalSum: UK, England, Northumberland (NE England), Amble (north, 4-6 miles off the coast)

NarNarrative: The Grayling is a freshwater fish related to the Salmon. It has a distinctive tall dorsal (back) fin, but in this specimen it is lying down, flat against the back. These fish grow to be 50cm (20ins) long. They feed on bottom-living insect larvae, shellfish and small fish.

The Greater Pipefish is a marine fish which has bony segmented armour encasing it, so the skeleton is hard to make out in most museum specimens. The mouth is at the end of a tube-like snout, suitable for catching small swimming animals. Like its relatives the Sea Horses, the males look after the eggs, hiding them in a brood pouch of soft flaps of skin under the tail.
LocalSum: UK, England, Northumberland (NE England), Blyth (3 miles off the coast)

NarNarrative: Meagres are large sea fish, up to 2metres (6.5feet) long. They live in shallow waters, such as the Mediterran, but are uncommon around the United Kingdom. The deep rumbling sounds they make can be heard up to 30metres (98ft) away underwater. Meagres are good food fish but few large specimens are found nowadays.

LocalSum: UK, England, Northumberland (NE England), Cresswell (north of), Druridge Bay

ColPhysicalDescription: Skull and pectoral fins and vertebrae (some).
Gill arches (with pharyngeal teeth and bristles).

NarNarrative: This is the skeleton of a Snipe Fish, so called because its snout is long and birdlike. These fish, which are related to pipefish, are about 15.0 cm long (6inches) and live in seas worldwide. This variety is occasionally found in british coastal waters where it feeds on small eggs and larvae in the plankton.

The Bowfin is like no other fish. It is not a true modern fish but an early bony one, an ancient survival. There is a wide bony plate between its lower jawbones that is not found in any other living fish, and the rest of its head is also covered with bony plates. The Bowfin is a freshwater fish, now only found in North America, feeding on various fish and invertebrates and growing up to 3 feet long. It spawns along the margins of lakes and streams. Its air bladder can act as a lung, so it can survive for as long as 24 hours in poorly aerated water or even out of the water altogether.

ColPhysicalDescription: Dentaries, right and left (joined in mid line).

NarNarrative: Angel Sharks are also known as Monkfish. Their bodies are flattened, and the front (pectoral) fins resemble the wings of angels or the hoods worn by monks. Angel Sharks live on the sea-bed in temperate (10-15?C) waters, usually partially buried in the sand so they can surprise their prey. They can grow up to 1.8 metres (6 ft.) long.

ColPhysicalDescription: Skull (cranium and rostrum only) and vertebrae (5).
SciName: Chordata & Pisces & Lamniformes & Unknown Pleurotremata : : : : Chordata

ColPhysicalDescription: Tooth plate, part, with 8 rows of teeth.

NarNarrative: Garpikes, or Gars, have heavy bony scales which lie side by side without overlapping as most fish scales do. They also have an air bladder to help adjust their buoyancy, which seems to be developed from the lung found in their relatives the lung fish. They lurk in shallow weedy fresh water in North America, where they lie in wait for their prey, which they can swim very fast to catch with their needle like teeth. The larger varieties can grow to 3.6M (12ft).

NarNarrative: These Sea Cucumbers look very different from the colourful animals they are in life.  This is because they lose most of their colour and shape when they are preserved in alcohol.
MulDescription: 'Dark brown adhesive residue is visible on the back of the specimen from the way it had previously been mounted

NarNarrative: This is a ragworm preserved in 'spirit' (a mixture of ethanol and methanol). Fishermen dig ragworms out of the lower part of the beach and use them as bait. Spirit preserves of the soft parts of an animal which would otherwise shrivel away, but the specimens often quickly lose their colour.
LocalSum: UK, England, South Shields, Black Middens
MulDescription: Preserving spirit has been topped up with 70% IMS
